{
  "What type of bond forms between sodium (Na) and chlorine (Cl)?": "",
  "Metallic bond": "",
  "Hydrogen bond": "",
  "Ionic bond": "",
  "Covalent bond": "",
  "Sodium is a metal with low electronegativity and chlorine is a nonmetal with high electronegativity. The large electronegativity difference causes electron transfer, forming an ionic bond.": "",
  "How many lone pairs does the oxygen atom in water (H₂O) have?": "",
  "1": "",
  "0": "",
  "3": "",
  "2": "",
  "Oxygen has 6 valence electrons. Two are used in bonding with hydrogen atoms, leaving 4 non-bonding electrons arranged as 2 lone pairs.": "",
  "Which type of bond involves the sharing of electrons between two nonmetal atoms?": "",
  "Coordinate bond only": "",
  "Covalent bonds form when two nonmetal atoms share one or more pairs of electrons. The sharing occurs because neither atom has a low enough ionization energy to fully transfer electrons.": "",
  "What is the bond order of the nitrogen-nitrogen bond in N₂?": "",
  "4": "",
  "N₂ contains a triple bond (one sigma and two pi bonds). Each nitrogen needs 3 more electrons to complete its octet, so they share 3 pairs of electrons, giving a bond order of 3.": "",
  "Which of the following molecules has a polar covalent bond?": "",
  "HCl": "",
  "Na₂O": "",
  "Cl₂": "",
  "N₂": "",
  "HCl has a polar covalent bond because chlorine is more electronegative than hydrogen, creating an unequal sharing of electrons. Cl₂ and N₂ are nonpolar covalent, and Na₂O is ionic.": "",
  "In a Lewis structure, how many total valence electrons does CO₂ have?": "",
  "16": "",
  "18": "",
  "12": "",
  "22": "",
  "Carbon has 4 valence electrons and each oxygen has 6. Total = 4 + 6 + 6 = 16 valence electrons, which are distributed as two double bonds and four lone pairs in the Lewis structure.": "",
  "Which bond is the shortest and strongest: C-C, C=C, or C≡C?": "",
  "C-C (single bond)": "",
  "C=C (double bond)": "",
  "They are all the same length and strength": "",
  "C≡C (triple bond)": "",
  "As bond order increases, the bond becomes shorter and stronger. A triple bond has more electron density between the nuclei than a double or single bond, pulling the atoms closer together.": "",
  "What does the octet rule state?": "",
  "Atoms always form 8 bonds": "",
  "Every atom must have exactly 8 electrons total": "",
  "Atoms tend to gain, lose, or share electrons to achieve 8 valence electrons": "",
  "Only noble gases can have 8 electrons": "",
  "The octet rule states that atoms tend to form bonds to achieve 8 electrons in their valence shell, mimicking the electron configuration of the nearest noble gas. Hydrogen is an exception, needing only 2.": "",
  "Which molecule is an exception to the octet rule by having an incomplete octet?": "",
  "BF₃": "",
  "H₂O": "",
  "NH₃": "",
  "CO₂": "",
  "In BF₃, boron has only 6 electrons in its valence shell (3 bonding pairs, no lone pairs). Boron is electron-deficient and is a common example of an incomplete octet.": "",
  "What type of bond is formed when one atom provides both electrons in a shared pair?": "",
  "Coordinate covalent (dative) bond": "",
  "Nonpolar covalent bond": "",
  "A coordinate covalent (dative) bond forms when one atom donates both electrons in a bonding pair. For example, in NH₄⁺, the nitrogen donates a lone pair to bond with the additional H⁺.": "",
  "What is an ionic bond?": "",
  "A bond formed by sharing electrons equally between atoms": "",
  "A weak attraction between polar molecules": "",
  "A bond formed by a sea of delocalized electrons": "",
  "A bond formed by the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions after electron transfer": "",
  "An ionic bond results from the complete transfer of electrons from a metal to a nonmetal, creating oppositely charged ions (cation and anion) that are held together by electrostatic attraction.": "",
  "What does 'bond polarity' mean?": "",
  "The equal distribution of electrons in a bond between identical atoms": "",
  "The number of bonds an atom can form": "",
  "The transfer of electrons from one atom to another": "",
  "The unequal sharing of electrons in a covalent bond due to a difference in electronegativity between the bonded atoms": "",
  "Bond polarity arises when two atoms in a covalent bond have different electronegativities. The more electronegative atom pulls electron density toward itself, creating partial charges (delta+ and delta-).": "",
  "What is a 'Lewis structure'?": "",
  "A diagram showing the nucleus and all electron shells": "",
  "A representation of only metallic bonds": "",
  "A diagram that uses dots and lines to represent valence electrons and bonds in a molecule": "",
  "A diagram showing only the arrangement of atoms in 3D space": "",
  "A Lewis structure shows valence electrons as dots and bonding pairs as lines between atoms. It helps predict molecular geometry, bond order, and the distribution of electrons in a molecule.": "",
  "What does 'formal charge' mean?": "",
  "The charge assigned to an atom in a Lewis structure assuming electrons are shared equally, calculated as valence electrons minus (lone pair electrons + half of bonding electrons)": "",
  "The electronegativity of the atom, as the dynamics involved tend to push conditions in this direction over time": "",
  "The total number of bonds an atom forms due to the well-established relationship between electrons trends and broader outcomes": "",
  "The actual charge on an ion in an ionic compound, although this interpretation oversimplifies the actual electrons mechanisms at work": "",
  "Formal charge = valence electrons - (lone pair electrons + 1/2 bonding electrons). It helps determine the most stable Lewis structure; the best structure minimizes formal charges on all atoms.": "",
  "What is 'resonance' in the context of Lewis structures?": "",
  "The oscillation of bond length over time within the broader context of resonance analysis": "",
  "The vibration of atoms in a molecule, which is consistent with how resonance mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "The alternation between ionic and covalent bonding, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The phenomenon where two or more valid Lewis structures can be drawn for a molecule, with the actual structure being a hybrid of all resonance forms": "",
  "Resonance occurs when multiple valid Lewis structures exist for a molecule, differing only in the placement of electrons (not atoms). The true structure is a weighted average (hybrid) of all resonance forms.": "",
  "What is a 'sigma bond'?": "",
  "A bond formed by the sideways overlap of p orbitals": "",
  "A bond formed by the head-on (end-to-end) overlap of orbitals along the internuclear axis": "",
  "A bond that exists only in double and triple bonds": "",
  "A bond found only in metallic substances": "",
  "A sigma bond is formed by head-on overlap of orbitals along the bond axis. It is the first bond formed between two atoms and is present in all single, double, and triple bonds.": "",
  "What is a 'pi bond'?": "",
  "The only type of bond in a single bond": "",
  "A bond formed by end-to-end overlap of s orbitals": "",
  "A bond formed between a metal and nonmetal": "",
  "A bond formed by the sideways (lateral) overlap of parallel p orbitals above and below the internuclear axis": "",
  "A pi bond results from the sideways overlap of parallel p orbitals. Pi bonds are found in double bonds (1 sigma + 1 pi) and triple bonds (1 sigma + 2 pi), and they restrict rotation.": "",
  "What does 'bond energy' refer to?": "",
  "The electronegativity difference between bonded atoms": "",
  "The energy released when a bond is formed": "",
  "The kinetic energy of bonded atoms": "",
  "The energy required to break one mole of a particular bond in the gas phase": "",
  "Bond energy (or bond dissociation energy) is the amount of energy required to break one mole of a specific bond in gaseous molecules. Higher bond energy indicates a stronger bond.": "",
  "What is a 'lattice energy'?": "",
  "The energy released when a covalent compound dissolves in water": "",
  "The energy required to melt a metallic solid": "",
  "The energy stored in the bonds of a crystal": "",
  "The energy released when gaseous ions come together to form one mole of a solid ionic compound": "",
  "Lattice energy is the energy released when gaseous cations and anions combine to form one mole of an ionic solid. Higher lattice energy indicates a more stable ionic compound.": "",
  "What does 'bond length' mean?": "",
  "The radius of the bonding orbital": "",
  "The distance between the nuclei of two bonded atoms at their equilibrium position": "",
  "The distance between two molecules in a solid": "",
  "The total length of all bonds in a molecule": "",
  "Bond length is the average distance between the nuclei of two bonded atoms at equilibrium. It depends on atomic radii and bond order; higher bond order leads to shorter bond length.": "",
  "A jeweler is comparing diamond and graphite, both made entirely of carbon. Diamond is the hardest natural substance while graphite is soft enough to use as pencil lead. Both contain covalent bonds. What difference in bonding structure accounts for these dramatically different properties?": "",
  "Diamond has a 3D network of sigma bonds (sp³) with each carbon bonded to 4 others, while graphite has layered sheets (sp²) with weak forces between layers": "",
  "Graphite has stronger bonds than diamond but in fewer directions": "",
  "Diamond has ionic bonds while graphite has covalent bonds": "",
  "Diamond and graphite have the same bonding but different isotopes of carbon": "",
  "In diamond, each carbon is sp³ hybridized and bonded to 4 neighbors in a rigid 3D tetrahedral network. In graphite, sp² carbons form flat sheets with weak London dispersion forces between layers, allowing them to slide.": "",
  "A food scientist is studying why table salt (NaCl) dissolves in water but not in oil. She considers the bonding in NaCl and the properties of both solvents. What explains NaCl's solubility in water but not in oil?": "",
  "NaCl has covalent bonds that are broken by water molecules": "",
  "Water molecules are polar and can stabilize the separated Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions through ion-dipole interactions, while nonpolar oil cannot": "",
  "NaCl forms metallic bonds with water but not oil": "",
  "Oil is too dense for NaCl to dissolve in": "",
  "NaCl is an ionic compound. Polar water molecules can surround and stabilize individual Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions through ion-dipole forces, overcoming the lattice energy. Nonpolar oil cannot provide these stabilizing interactions.": "",
  "An engineer designing a new ceramic material needs to maximize strength and melting point. She compares MgO and NaCl, both ionic compounds. MgO has a melting point of 2852°C while NaCl melts at 801°C. What bonding difference explains MgO's much higher melting point?": "",
  "MgO has covalent bonds while NaCl has ionic bonds within the broader context of higher analysis": "",
  "MgO has 2+ and 2- charges and smaller ionic radii, resulting in much stronger electrostatic attraction (higher lattice energy) than NaCl's 1+ and 1- charges": "",
  "MgO is heavier than NaCl, so it requires more energy to melt without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "MgO has more atoms per formula unit than NaCl when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "MgO has Mg²⁺ and O²⁻ ions (higher charges) and smaller ionic radii than Na⁺ and Cl⁻. By Coulomb's law, the lattice energy increases with higher charge and smaller distance, making MgO much harder to melt.": "",
  "A chemist synthesizes ozone (O₃) and needs to describe its bonding. She draws two resonance structures where the double bond alternates between the two terminal oxygens. If both resonance structures are equally valid, what is the actual O-O bond order in ozone?": "",
  "1 (single bond)": "",
  "3 (triple bond)": "",
  "2 (double bond)": "",
  "1.5 (between single and double)": "",
  "Ozone has two equivalent resonance structures, each with one single and one double bond. The actual structure is a resonance hybrid with a bond order of (2+1)/2 = 1.5 for each O-O bond.": "",
  "A biomedical researcher is studying the oxygen-carrying protein hemoglobin. The iron(II) ion at its center forms a coordinate covalent bond with O₂. In this bond, oxygen donates a lone pair to the iron. Why is this classified as a coordinate covalent bond rather than a regular covalent bond?": "",
  "Because the bond is weaker than a normal covalent bond": "",
  "Because iron is a metal and oxygen is a nonmetal": "",
  "Because the bond involves electron transfer from iron to oxygen": "",
  "Because one atom (oxygen) donates both electrons in the bonding pair rather than each atom contributing one": "",
  "In a coordinate covalent bond, one atom provides both electrons in the shared pair. Here, oxygen has lone pairs it can donate to the empty d orbitals of Fe²⁺, forming a dative bond.": "",
  "A polymer chemist is comparing polyethylene (with C-C single bonds) and Kevlar (with extensive C=C and C=N bonds and hydrogen bonding). Kevlar is used in bulletproof vests. Why does the presence of double bonds and hydrogen bonding make Kevlar so much stronger?": "",
  "Double bonds are weaker and more flexible than single bonds": "",
  "Polyethylene is heavier, making it weaker per unit mass": "",
  "Double bonds create rigidity and prevent rotation, while hydrogen bonds between chains create a strong, ordered structure": "",
  "Kevlar has ionic bonds that are stronger than covalent bonds": "",
  "Pi bonds in double bonds restrict rotation, creating rigid polymer chains. Hydrogen bonds between adjacent chains align them and hold them tightly together, creating Kevlar's exceptional tensile strength.": "",
  "A student is comparing the boiling points of NaCl (1413°C), SiO₂ (2230°C), and CO₂ (-78.5°C sublimation). All contain bonds between elements with significant electronegativity differences. Why does CO₂ have such a low sublimation point compared to the other two?": "",
  "CO₂ has ionic bonds that break easily at low temperatures": "",
